WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.200
So yeah, we'll have our first keynote.

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:11.680
So Isabel Zimmerman is a senior software engineer at Posit and a major contributor to open source

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.360
and champion of open source.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.680
We're really lucky and excited to have her.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:18.559
So Isabel, let's have a round of applause.

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:19.559
Isabel Zimmerman-PyData Global 2025-2025

00:00:19.559 --> 00:00:21.040
I did data science for a while.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:27.400
I transitioned into doing data science tool making because I just really love tools.

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:33.840
I was actually the first full-time Python open source hire at Posit.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:36.919
And this was at a time where this company was still called RStudio.

00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:42.560
We actually already had people who were building Python stuff, but I was the first person who

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:47.560
was dedicated full-time for solely novel open source Python work.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:52.919
I started out building MLOps packages, but nowadays I'm spending most of my time building

00:00:52.919 --> 00:00:55.439
the Python experience in different IDEs.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:01:01.279
And I have to say, my love of tools is not really constrained just to computers.

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:05.959
If you haven't noticed, there's a giant magical goose on this slide.

00:01:05.959 --> 00:01:07.720
I am a huge fantasy reader.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:14.199
I'm actually flying to Boston from Salt Lake City, Utah for a fantasy conference.

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:19.239
And one of my favorite fantasy books, there's this magical earring, no spoilers, but there's

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:23.480
this magical earring that's passed down from generation to generation.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.279
And it turns out that this small little thing can beat the big evil bad guy at the end of

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:29.279
the book.

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:33.519
And I think there's something really special about having something in hand, even if it

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:40.199
doesn't feel like the craziest, most magical tool, that can help solve a problem.

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:44.940
And so I assume you're here not to hear about my favorite fantasy books, but probably because

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:51.559
you are either a Python user or someone who uses and loves data or some Venn diagram overlap

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:53.839
of these two.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:58.900
And maybe you're thinking, you know, like, why do I even care about the tools I use?

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:01.160
You know, this is a whole talk about them.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.860
Why dedicate all of this time and energy?

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:09.320
And so just off the bat, like, I consider a tool anything that you can use to carry

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:12.720
out a particular function.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.880
You know, this talk is about tool users and tool builders.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:20.419
And maybe you identify with one of these identities, like, more than the other.

00:02:20.419 --> 00:02:21.779
And they're not mutually exclusive.

00:02:21.779 --> 00:02:27.699
But if you think about caring about using tools, maybe you feel more strongly about

00:02:27.699 --> 00:02:28.699
this identity.

00:02:28.699 --> 00:02:31.919
You know, I'm someone who consumes these things.

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:36.779
If we think of this as, like, some sort of fantasy story, the villain in our tool user

00:02:36.779 --> 00:02:42.979
persona would be the inertia of only using the tools that you already know because, you

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:44.059
know, it's easier.

00:02:44.059 --> 00:02:46.139
You already know them.

00:02:46.139 --> 00:02:52.860
And so I'd like to consider that using tools and picking tools thoughtfully is very important.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:56.899
And choosing the right one will make your life way easier.

00:02:56.899 --> 00:03:02.779
So I'm someone who probably like most of you, when you get out into this data science world,

00:03:02.779 --> 00:03:04.979
you start using something called Pandas.

00:03:04.979 --> 00:03:09.380
And this is a data frame library that, you know, it's what I was taught in school.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:13.460
It's like one of the most popular libraries out there for Python.

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:15.460
And I thought it was a great place to start.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:18.300
And it served me very well for a long time.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:20.899
The data I was working with started to get bigger.

00:03:20.899 --> 00:03:24.740
And Pandas started to feel a little bit slower, a little bit clunkier.

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.220
So I ended up changing over to something called Polars.

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:30.500
The syntax is very similar.

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:33.460
But it's built on Rust and it's a little bit faster.

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:34.740
And this was a simple switch.

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:37.220
You know, a lot of the API is the same.

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:42.539
But it made my life feel a little bit faster.

00:03:42.619 --> 00:03:47.500
Everyone sits somewhere on the spectrum of building and using tools.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:51.979
And maybe you don't identify immediately as somebody who is building tools.

00:03:51.979 --> 00:03:54.300
But I'd like to convince you otherwise.

00:03:54.300 --> 00:04:00.380
One, I think it's important for everyone to even think of themselves as like a little bit of a tool builder.

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:04.059
By building a tool for yourself, you can speed up your own work.

00:04:04.059 --> 00:04:08.460
And speed up not only your work today, but your work for future you.

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:12.139
The barrier to building a tool has never been lower with the help of AI.

00:04:12.539 --> 00:04:18.859
Your cloud, your copilot, your chat GPT is able to help you build Python packages if you don't know where to start.

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:25.019
And this tool doesn't have to be something that's widely shared into the world.

00:04:25.019 --> 00:04:26.859
It can be something that's just for yourself.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:35.100
As part of my own personal book nerdiness, I actually rebind books as well.

00:04:35.739 --> 00:04:40.459
And I have to do specific measurements for, like, the cover, the back, the spine,

00:04:40.459 --> 00:04:42.220
and all of these little hinges in between.

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:46.459
And I like a very specific, like, 7 millimeter gutter.

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:50.700
And all of the tools out there are all 5 millimeter.

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:56.140
So I made this silly little, like, literal piece of plastic to help me make my own books.

00:04:56.859 --> 00:04:59.260
It's something only I will ever use.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:00.940
But it helps me every day.

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:01.980
Well, maybe not every day.

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:05.019
Every day I'm doing hobbies to make these books better.

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:08.299
So your tools don't have to be anything fancy.

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:11.339
And also, you might already be building them.

00:05:11.339 --> 00:05:15.100
Maybe you're someone like me who is fat fingering Git push all the time.

00:05:16.059 --> 00:05:21.420
And now has an alias on their computer so that when you write GTI push, it actually uses Git instead.

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:26.299
You know, if you're writing code, you're building something.

00:05:27.179 --> 00:05:30.299
You know, a dashboard or a report, that's a tool.

00:05:30.299 --> 00:05:32.859
You know, it's a tool used to make business decisions.

00:05:32.859 --> 00:05:37.739
Maybe you have a function that you've been slacking back and forth with your coworkers.

00:05:37.739 --> 00:05:42.140
That's a tool that you've been, you know, helping streamline your data workflows.

00:05:42.779 --> 00:05:44.459
Or maybe something else entirely.

00:05:44.459 --> 00:05:47.100
So these are all tools you might already be making.

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:53.500
And when I transitioned from, like, a data scientist persona to a tool builder persona,

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:55.820
I thought that I knew what mattered.

00:05:56.859 --> 00:05:58.779
I had already filled my bag with lots of tools.

00:05:58.779 --> 00:06:00.459
You know, I could do this.

00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:04.059
I could write clean code.

00:06:04.059 --> 00:06:05.420
I could design APIs.

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:07.660
I knew how to optimize performance.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:12.459
And I thought, you know, if my code works, people will use it.

00:06:13.579 --> 00:06:19.420
And we actually do a fair amount of user testing at Posit, where we'll watch someone use tools.

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:24.859
And I have watched truly, like, the most brilliant people that I look up to so much

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:29.820
get confused about a tool because a button is in the wrong spot.

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:33.820
Or, you know, you press refresh and it only refreshes, like,

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:37.179
the first layer of your namespace and not the whole namespace.

00:06:37.179 --> 00:06:38.059
Or just something.

00:06:39.179 --> 00:06:40.140
And people get stuck.

00:06:40.859 --> 00:06:42.220
That's a part of life.

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:45.739
Tools are imperfect because they're built by imperfect people.

00:06:45.739 --> 00:06:47.339
And you are an imperfect user.

00:06:47.339 --> 00:06:51.260
And I think that is, like, the most beautiful thing to think about.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:55.019
Because if we are both imperfect on kind of both sides of this coin,

00:06:55.019 --> 00:06:59.019
that means that there are skills there that we can build and that we can learn.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:07.100
So, if you're, like, writing your resume, we often think about things in the scale of,

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:10.779
like, there's hard skills and then there's soft skills.

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:15.660
You know, hard skills are things like, I know how to use scikit-learn.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:17.100
I write C++ code.

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.579
And soft skills are, like, I can lead a team.

00:07:19.579 --> 00:07:21.579
Or I'm really good at writing documentation.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:25.420
And there is a lot of baggage around these terms that I want to address.

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:28.619
You know, LinkedIn, it feels like swaps every year.

00:07:28.619 --> 00:07:31.100
Half the time they say, all you need are hard skills.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:32.619
We don't care about soft skills anymore.

00:07:32.619 --> 00:07:34.380
And then it's, all you need are soft skills.

00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:35.899
We don't care about hard skills anymore.

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:39.579
And I'm not interested today in, like, really convincing you of one or the other.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:44.299
But more thinking about this dichotomy of the ways that we're working.

00:07:45.739 --> 00:07:49.420
And when I was thinking about this talk and, like, how to talk about tools,

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:52.859
I realized that tools have these same hard and soft skills.

00:07:53.579 --> 00:07:56.700
So, your hard skills and tools are these computer elements.

00:07:56.700 --> 00:08:00.459
Things like modularity, reproducibility, flexibility.

00:08:01.019 --> 00:08:04.459
Whereas the soft skills are more of these human elements of your tools.

00:08:05.019 --> 00:08:08.220
Things like knowing your user, understanding their needs,

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:12.380
delighting in the small things, and explaining your work.

00:08:13.260 --> 00:08:14.140
And here's the thing.

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:19.420
Your tools, to be, you know, really delightful tools that people love to use,

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:23.420
have to have both these hard skills and the soft ones.

00:08:23.899 --> 00:08:24.140
All right.

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.700
So, we'll start with what a tool's hard skills are.

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:28.940
With modularity.

00:08:30.779 --> 00:08:33.900
So, when you're building a tool, a lot of times the first thing you have to think of

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:35.900
is, like, where are we starting from?

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:39.979
And one of the first Python packages I was building is called Vediver.

00:08:39.979 --> 00:08:41.659
And it's an MLOps framework.

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:43.979
And there's this element of, like, building APIs.

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:49.179
And I had to decide, you know, where are these APIs coming from?

00:08:49.179 --> 00:08:52.219
I could, of course, you know, go spend all this time building a tool,

00:08:52.539 --> 00:08:58.059
go spend all this time research, build out my own, like, REST API generation.

00:08:58.059 --> 00:09:03.659
But I realized there's so many fantastic community tools out there that I can leverage what's

00:09:03.659 --> 00:09:08.140
already been built in the open source community and be able to have this relentless focus

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:09.739
on the MLOps side of the work.

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:15.340
So, for tool builders, finding tools that, you know, work with what you already know

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:16.619
is super important.

00:09:16.619 --> 00:09:21.979
And as a user, it's also really important to maybe understand what your tools are being

00:09:21.979 --> 00:09:24.940
built off of, to have these clear extension points.

00:09:26.859 --> 00:09:31.260
Tomorrow morning, one of my colleagues, Jules, is going to be giving a talk about how to

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:36.219
build an extension package for different Python packages.

00:09:36.219 --> 00:09:40.539
I would love for 2026 to be, like, the year of Python extension packages.

00:09:40.539 --> 00:09:44.140
I want to see everyone making specialized tools for what they know.

00:09:45.979 --> 00:09:49.979
Because it is it makes your life a lot easier when something works exactly for you.

00:09:52.059 --> 00:09:57.340
The other good thing about modularity is if we think about Legos, you know, you can connect

00:09:57.340 --> 00:09:58.299
them to themselves.

00:09:58.299 --> 00:10:03.179
So, if you're building on a modular surface, you're able to have a tool that grows with

00:10:03.179 --> 00:10:03.739
your user.

00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:08.539
Like in the Vetiver case, I can think of, you know, you can do all these cool things

00:10:08.539 --> 00:10:10.380
with models, like what I've added.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:15.500
But you're also able to make really complex APIs because of the basics of FastAPI.

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:17.580
Okay.

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:19.099
So, this is a talk about tools.

00:10:19.099 --> 00:10:23.500
And it's only fair for me to eventually introduce the tool that I spend most of my day job on.

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.419
And that's an IDE called Positron.

00:10:25.979 --> 00:10:29.900
So, Positron is an IDE built specifically for data science.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:33.900
And if you're a VS Code user, it might look a little bit familiar.

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:41.820
It is a VS Code fork, and it has things, different elements, like this variables pane, this plots

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:46.940
pane, including a film strip on the side, and this built-in console, along with many

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:53.020
other goodies that we've added to help emphasize this data science experience.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:11:01.340
But we built off of the basics of code OSS, which is this open source VS Code.

00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:06.460
And it's useful for us because we are able to, again, have this relentless focus on the

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:07.820
data science experience.

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:14.219
But also, it's helpful for users because they can plug into this huge ecosystem of

00:11:14.219 --> 00:11:17.659
open VSX and VS Code extensions.

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:22.219
Something that we've gotten for free because of this is, like, the idea of growing and

00:11:22.219 --> 00:11:24.859
outgrowing your laptop through remote SSH.

00:11:24.859 --> 00:11:30.619
And another one of my colleagues tomorrow is going to be giving a talk on Positron and

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:31.900
remote SSH.

00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:34.700
It's Rodrigo's talk tomorrow, I think, at 9 a.m.

00:11:35.659 --> 00:11:36.299
Or 11.

00:11:36.299 --> 00:11:37.260
I'm so sorry.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:38.059
One of those two.

00:11:38.859 --> 00:11:46.700
So alongside reproducibility, alongside of modularity, we also want reproducibility.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:49.739
And data science folks know all about reproducibility.

00:11:49.739 --> 00:11:56.140
We think about it and how it is, like, the foundational thing for, like, trustworthy

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:56.859
science.

00:11:56.859 --> 00:12:02.380
You know, there's a strong pull for exploring data in reproducible ways.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:06.380
But there's also, like, this tension because there's a lot of really cool ways to explore

00:12:06.619 --> 00:12:11.419
data with a GUI, where, you know, I'm going to load the CSV and I'm going to click around.

00:12:11.419 --> 00:12:13.099
And it's a little bit of a mismatch.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:20.059
We can think about, you know, when we're doing data science or when we're doing data

00:12:20.059 --> 00:12:24.140
work, where are we doing steps that are not reproducible?

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:29.099
Maybe you're loading your data from a CSV in Pandas.

00:12:29.099 --> 00:12:30.940
You're doing some exploration.

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:33.900
And then you're exporting it to Excel and making a table there.

00:12:34.299 --> 00:12:38.219
I would encourage you to think about this workflow, the places where when you tell your

00:12:38.219 --> 00:12:42.700
colleagues about it, it's, okay, download this and then click and then click and then

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:46.380
click, because those are the things that are going to be less reproducible over time.

00:12:47.179 --> 00:12:51.979
There's an open source package called Great Tables that allows you to move directly from,

00:12:51.979 --> 00:12:58.700
you know, building your data exploration with Pandas or Pollers right into a table, or if

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:00.619
you want to use plots or something like that.

00:13:00.619 --> 00:13:06.619
So thinking really about completing your whole cycle in Python or in some sort of language

00:13:06.619 --> 00:13:12.219
where you can pass this off as a reproducible artifact, rather than saying, okay, here are

00:13:12.219 --> 00:13:16.700
all of the steps to click all of the right buttons to get your data in the right place.

00:13:19.179 --> 00:13:22.059
In Positron, there's something called a data explorer.

00:13:22.059 --> 00:13:27.099
And when we first built it, there was a little bit of this trap of like, look at how beautiful

00:13:27.099 --> 00:13:27.580
this is.

00:13:27.580 --> 00:13:29.020
It can handle millions of rows.

00:13:29.179 --> 00:13:31.820
It can handle millions of columns.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:33.419
You can add filters.

00:13:33.419 --> 00:13:35.500
Here I'm looking at different literary prizes.

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:37.659
You know, I want to look at Booker Prize winners.

00:13:38.859 --> 00:13:42.780
I'm able to look at my data in ascending or descending order.

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:47.179
It's a great place to do quick data exploration.

00:13:47.179 --> 00:13:51.260
But if you notice, it's a lot of, you know, if I was telling a colleague, I would say,

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:53.179
add this filter, add this filter.

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:57.820
So we added this button where you can convert to code, where because all of these filters

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:03.979
are in a very modular, built in a very modular way, it has a one-to-one balance of I can

00:14:03.979 --> 00:14:07.020
click this button because I know what the filters are.

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:13.419
I can generate code, not using AI, just using like a tree to have code that works and runs

00:14:13.419 --> 00:14:17.340
and generates the same data exploration every single time.

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:22.539
So I think this is a really interesting way to like bridge the gap between GUI exploration

00:14:22.539 --> 00:14:24.380
and having a reproducible output.

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:25.979
And flexibility.

00:14:26.940 --> 00:14:30.700
When I think of flexibility, I think of like a Swiss Army knife, perhaps, in tools.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:38.859
So it's convenient, you know, a Swiss Army knife, you can have scissors and a bottle opener and a

00:14:39.419 --> 00:14:43.340
knife or whatever else you need for your little tasks to open the boxes.

00:14:44.619 --> 00:14:50.059
And, you know, I'm pro Swiss Army knife, but you're not going to use a Swiss Army knife

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:51.419
to build a house.

00:14:51.419 --> 00:14:55.340
So you have to kind of think about what kind of flexibility works well in the projects

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:55.979
that you're building.

00:14:57.419 --> 00:15:00.460
And if you're not aware, there's something called the Zen of Python.

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:02.780
If you type import this, it will print it out.

00:15:04.219 --> 00:15:09.099
And it has these kind of core values of how to use Python as a language.

00:15:09.099 --> 00:15:13.500
And one of the ones that's really interesting to me is that simple is better than complex,

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:15.500
complex is better than complicated.

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:20.460
And I know that this slide says flexibility, and I really do want to encourage you to use

00:15:21.419 --> 00:15:21.900
that.

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:26.460
But I also want people to think really thoughtfully about the kind of information that they're

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:31.179
ingesting in terms of when you're writing functions or something like that.

00:15:32.219 --> 00:15:35.979
Lucas Lenga, there's a PyCon keynote from 2022.

00:15:35.979 --> 00:15:39.179
I highly recommend it if you ever write any types in your code.

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:46.780
And he really talks about like a function that has insane types is probably a code smell of

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:50.299
you need to break this down and make your code slightly less flexible.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:55.179
And I did fall into this trap, you know, when I was starting to build tools, I would write

00:15:55.179 --> 00:15:59.260
a function and I would type it and I would see these crazy unions where I'm supporting

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:04.460
polar's data frames and panda's data frames and like lists and dictionaries and tuples

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:05.580
and all of it.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:10.539
When I really should have focused on building kind of modular things for each function and

00:16:10.539 --> 00:16:12.940
then combining them in a more clever way.

00:16:14.059 --> 00:16:18.859
Because if you have something that accepts really complex inputs, it's going to be way

00:16:18.859 --> 00:16:22.140
harder to also support very complex tasks.

00:16:23.739 --> 00:16:28.059
I think the rise of AI tools recently has highlighted the importance of starting with

00:16:28.059 --> 00:16:33.419
a reasonable amount of context and then letting users configure more or less information.

00:16:34.619 --> 00:16:38.539
Something that we've noticed is like AI often does not have all of the right context for

00:16:38.539 --> 00:16:39.419
data science work.

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:44.700
If it's only doing static analysis, it only knows that there is some sort of data frame

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:48.059
called data and it's getting this information from this URL.

00:16:48.859 --> 00:16:53.900
So in Positron, there's this thing called Positron Assistant and it gives the LLMs a

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:55.340
little bit of your data.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:01.500
It gives them images from your plots and whatever else you want in order to get the most out

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:03.580
of AI for your data experience.

00:17:04.219 --> 00:17:08.140
This kind of has like this happy path or we think of it as like a pit of success.

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:12.619
So if you just open this up, it will have the context that's important for your model

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:15.900
to make better information for like a better output.

00:17:16.699 --> 00:17:18.300
But also we care about privacy.

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:22.300
So we need a really clear way to add and remove context.

00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:25.739
So you can see I'm like clicking this eye open and closed.

00:17:25.739 --> 00:17:31.180
So say you can see this information, you can't see this information or adding in different

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:31.900
context.

00:17:33.579 --> 00:17:38.540
So these are what I think of as the hard skills, hard skills of a tool.

00:17:39.819 --> 00:17:44.380
And there is one thing that is front of mind that I've touched on very briefly, but that

00:17:44.459 --> 00:17:49.420
is the fact that AI 2025 is the era of AI everything.

00:17:51.099 --> 00:17:54.780
You know, if you're writing code these days and it's out in the world, it will probably

00:17:54.780 --> 00:18:00.939
be read by AI assistants or perhaps it's being read by Amazon Bedrock, by your local models

00:18:00.939 --> 00:18:01.500
or whatever.

00:18:02.459 --> 00:18:04.780
And AI is really good at these strong skills.

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:09.979
If you can almost use them as like keywords to get better output from your LLM, you know,

00:18:09.979 --> 00:18:14.140
make this function more flexible, make this function more modular.

00:18:14.859 --> 00:18:21.020
But what AI does really struggle with, even with the right context, is what users actually

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:22.619
need are these soft skills.

00:18:23.979 --> 00:18:28.140
So great tools require technical excellence, but also user empathy.

00:18:28.859 --> 00:18:34.300
And I was looking at the stack overflow survey, you know, there's 25,000 responses.

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:39.099
And these are things that people do not plan to use AI ever for this task.

00:18:39.979 --> 00:18:45.180
It looks like developers are showing kind of the most resistance to these high responsibility

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:47.979
systemic tasks like deployment and monitoring.

00:18:47.979 --> 00:18:50.219
But also really interesting is project planning.

00:18:51.339 --> 00:18:56.939
And I think part of project planning, in my mind, my hypothesis, is that, you know, project

00:18:56.939 --> 00:18:58.939
planning is a lot of the soft skills.

00:18:58.939 --> 00:19:03.739
Project planning is realizing, you know, my stakeholders need this output.

00:19:03.739 --> 00:19:08.300
My stakeholders think this is important or I think this is important.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:13.979
Or that product knowledge that you carry with yourself and with your team, kind of

00:19:13.979 --> 00:19:19.500
these, you know, these soft skills that AI is not able to take over for us.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:25.900
So when we think about the soft skills, I really want people to think about, you know,

00:19:25.900 --> 00:19:27.500
the human side of a tool.

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:31.020
And the first thing is to know your users.

00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:36.300
At Posit, a lot of us were data scientists, so we have a lot of, like, data science knowledge.

00:19:36.300 --> 00:19:40.540
So we really intimately know the struggles of, you know, like, what we were running into.

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:45.900
And I think something interesting here is, like, the difference between a data scientist

00:19:45.900 --> 00:19:47.579
and a software engineer.

00:19:47.579 --> 00:19:53.099
Data work inherently looks a little bit different than what we would consider software engineer

00:19:53.099 --> 00:19:53.660
work.

00:19:53.660 --> 00:19:58.699
Data practitioners are more on, like, exploring uncharted territory.

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:01.099
Uncharted territories.

00:20:01.819 --> 00:20:05.180
They do a lot of iteration and a lot of experimentation.

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:10.219
And then software engineers, we can think of them as, like, building castles in, you

00:20:10.219 --> 00:20:11.339
know, known lands.

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:16.619
Things that involve a lot of structure and things that have a very specific outcome.

00:20:17.819 --> 00:20:20.939
So you're not going to give your cartographer a mason's tools.

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:24.300
So knowing your users is really important.

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:26.699
And if you don't know, it's okay to ask.

00:20:26.699 --> 00:20:30.619
I think that's very, like, a very thoughtful way to approach this problem.

00:20:32.939 --> 00:20:37.420
You know, for us, we realize that a tool that's built for software engineers might not be

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.219
the best fit for someone who needs to do a lot of experimentation.

00:20:41.739 --> 00:20:47.020
And one way we really wanted to show data scientists that, like, we understand their

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:51.979
struggles and something that I use almost daily is having a permanent console available

00:20:51.979 --> 00:20:52.780
in Positron.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:57.979
So if you're not familiar with having some sort of iPython console, you can think of

00:20:57.979 --> 00:21:03.420
it as sort of a, like, Jupyter notebook light that's built in, that's always on, that's

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:07.579
activated all the time, available in your IDE.

00:21:08.619 --> 00:21:13.819
So in this little GIF, I'm, like, just mashing shift or command enter all the way down.

00:21:13.819 --> 00:21:16.300
If I was on Windows, it would be control enter.

00:21:16.300 --> 00:21:18.300
And you can see I can run this line by line.

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:23.819
This plot is, like, slowly getting built up as I'm executing different pieces of it.

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:28.699
And it's really, like, built for this quick experimentation.

00:21:28.699 --> 00:21:31.099
I'm also able to go down there and type in this console.

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:34.780
And it's fully syntax highlighted.

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:36.619
You're able to get code completions there.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:43.579
And we've actually made changes to the LSP or language server protocol inside the IDE

00:21:43.579 --> 00:21:46.540
so that it's optimized for data science use.

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:51.260
This is all things that we realize, you know, data scientists, if they're using a data frame

00:21:51.260 --> 00:21:56.699
and they have either a period or, you know, your brackets, they probably will want a column.

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:01.500
So we focused on, you know, making sure column completions come to the front.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:08.060
And just these little things that really show that, you know, we know how data scientists

00:22:08.060 --> 00:22:11.660
work because, you know, a lot of us are data scientists or were data scientists.

00:22:11.979 --> 00:22:14.780
And discoverability is a lot of this work.

00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:19.500
So when you're thinking about sharing a report or thinking about building a tool,

00:22:20.619 --> 00:22:24.780
you want to really, like, be this little goose that's shining your lantern on the path that

00:22:24.780 --> 00:22:26.140
should be traveled the most.

00:22:26.939 --> 00:22:29.260
This is really kind of a subset of knowing your user.

00:22:30.459 --> 00:22:34.060
And all of these soft skills really come from a place of empathy for the people who are using

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:35.819
the tools that you're building.

00:22:35.819 --> 00:22:39.500
Or thinking about how you want your tools to be used.

00:22:39.500 --> 00:22:43.739
Or thinking about how you want your tool to support you as you're using it.

00:22:45.819 --> 00:22:51.420
So for discoverability, we ought to think about, like, what will users care about?

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:52.540
And how can we find them?

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:57.739
Decide how can we help them find things that are not immediately obvious?

00:22:58.459 --> 00:23:00.780
Discoverability really is an eternal quest.

00:23:01.739 --> 00:23:06.140
Your hidden features are going to be, like, secret passages.

00:23:06.300 --> 00:23:09.900
Just because there's treasure at the end of this tunnel, if nobody knows it's there,

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:11.979
nobody's going to find it.

00:23:13.579 --> 00:23:15.900
So discoverability is really hard.

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:21.099
In documentation, in the actual API, in the UI of an app that you might be deploying.

00:23:22.459 --> 00:23:26.459
Documentation is really helpful, but it's also equally important to have things that

00:23:26.459 --> 00:23:28.380
are, like, self-documenting.

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:33.339
So when you're using a tool, we want to think about, are things easy for me to remember

00:23:33.339 --> 00:23:35.500
so I'm not looking at the docs every single time?

00:23:37.099 --> 00:23:40.300
Information can be hard to find and retain.

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:43.420
So bringing to the front of what actually gets used is super important.

00:23:46.219 --> 00:23:50.540
So we want to think about, like, what are things that are high impact but hard to find?

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:52.219
Or things that are constantly used?

00:23:53.660 --> 00:23:59.660
There's a project called Quarto that is an open source, like, publishing and authoring

00:23:59.660 --> 00:24:00.459
platform.

00:24:00.459 --> 00:24:02.939
It's actually how I've built all of my slides.

00:24:02.939 --> 00:24:05.260
It's how I've built my website.

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:06.859
You can build dashboards with it.

00:24:06.859 --> 00:24:10.060
You can integrate it with different applications, like Shiny.

00:24:11.579 --> 00:24:16.219
And it's a really beautiful tool that we wanted people to have a great authoring experience

00:24:16.219 --> 00:24:17.180
in Positron with.

00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:23.819
So here you can see that it looks like just a markdown file that you're also able to run

00:24:23.819 --> 00:24:24.300
code in.

00:24:24.939 --> 00:24:27.900
I honestly, I could give a whole other talk about how much I love Quarto.

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:29.579
It is one of my favorite things to use.

00:24:31.739 --> 00:24:34.939
But there's a lot of settings and there's a lot of ways to use Quarto.

00:24:35.339 --> 00:24:39.739
And when I'm building out something like these slides, a lot of times I'm making changes

00:24:39.739 --> 00:24:41.180
and then I'm pressing save.

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:43.099
And I'll make changes and I'm pressing save.

00:24:43.099 --> 00:24:49.500
And when you're rendering these slides locally, that is kind of annoying to, like, bring down

00:24:49.500 --> 00:24:51.979
my whole little local host and, like, restart it.

00:24:52.619 --> 00:24:56.780
So we have this editor action bar where you can see there's this preview, this render

00:24:56.780 --> 00:24:57.339
on save.

00:24:57.339 --> 00:25:00.859
You can toggle between source and visual, insert a code cell.

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:05.339
We wanted to think about, you know, what is important for users.

00:25:05.979 --> 00:25:09.979
If you're using something like this, you're probably wanting to run code and markdown.

00:25:09.979 --> 00:25:12.219
So we're going to have a button to insert a code cell.

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:16.619
We also want to high, like, elevate the setting of render on save.

00:25:16.619 --> 00:25:21.979
It's not the, like, biggest feature, you know, people aren't going to Positron saying, wow,

00:25:21.979 --> 00:25:23.579
I can render on save now.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:28.540
But being able to elevate this because we think it's important for users for their own

00:25:29.500 --> 00:25:30.140
workflow.

00:25:32.619 --> 00:25:37.099
We're also making different UI changes to, like, how our Jupyter notebooks look and to

00:25:37.099 --> 00:25:43.339
help ease discovery and have this package use have our Jupyter notebook experience feel

00:25:43.339 --> 00:25:44.219
good for you.

00:25:44.219 --> 00:25:48.140
So if you have big opinions on Jupyter notebooks, we'd love to talk to you at the Posit booth.

00:25:52.060 --> 00:25:55.660
Next, we'll talk about having letting little things have big impact.

00:25:56.300 --> 00:26:00.699
So sometimes a tool can kind of feel like death by a thousand paper cuts.

00:26:00.699 --> 00:26:04.619
You know, each tiny drop of improvement is a sort of healing solve.

00:26:05.819 --> 00:26:10.619
If you've ever I know when I was learning Pandas, every single time that I tried to

00:26:10.619 --> 00:26:15.979
do a join, I would have to go to the documentation because it just didn't quite feel ergonomic

00:26:15.979 --> 00:26:19.579
to me coming from, like, more SQL-y or R background.

00:26:20.459 --> 00:26:23.660
And I was just like, oh, I wish I could remember this a little bit better.

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:29.020
And I think this is a really cool way to think about, like, how can we find these little

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:31.579
things that can make a big impact in our projects?

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:37.339
So we have to do the painful things and we have to do the painful things more often.

00:26:37.900 --> 00:26:40.939
And it's funny because there's two big things that happen when you do these painful

00:26:40.939 --> 00:26:41.739
things.

00:26:41.739 --> 00:26:48.140
One, you either get really good at doing hard things or you discover a new way to make the

00:26:48.140 --> 00:26:49.500
hard thing a little bit easier.

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:56.380
So one thing that was small but really annoying was if you've ever used an IDE and you're,

00:26:56.380 --> 00:27:00.380
you know, running just, like, a regular script and you click this little play button and

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:03.979
it'll either run it, you know, in the terminal or in Positron, you can also run it in the

00:27:03.979 --> 00:27:04.540
console.

00:27:06.459 --> 00:27:09.500
And, like, 99% of the time, that's super great.

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:14.300
All I want is this play button to run my Python file in my terminal.

00:27:14.540 --> 00:27:21.660
But sometimes I'm building a Streamlit app or a Dash app or Shiny app or a Fast API or

00:27:21.660 --> 00:27:22.619
Flask or whatever.

00:27:23.339 --> 00:27:27.900
And, you know, when you click that button, it actually just runs the Python file.

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:30.219
It doesn't actually start the application.

00:27:30.219 --> 00:27:33.979
And I know some people have, like, changed their API because of this because it's kind

00:27:33.979 --> 00:27:34.540
of annoying.

00:27:35.579 --> 00:27:40.540
But something that we built in that we thought was interesting was that when you press the

00:27:40.780 --> 00:27:46.780
button, it actually runs, you know, Streamlit, run app, you know, in your terminal rather

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:48.699
than just running the Python file itself.

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:54.540
So this is something that, you know, it's a small, small change.

00:27:54.540 --> 00:28:00.459
But if you think about people who have used this package or people who are reading your

00:28:00.459 --> 00:28:05.020
reports or something like that, you can think about what are things that people say, oh,

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:07.099
I have to click a couple times for.

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:09.020
And maybe it's not even a complaint.

00:28:09.020 --> 00:28:10.540
It's just an observation.

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:17.500
Being able to minimize those small paper cuts really makes a big impact time over time.

00:28:22.459 --> 00:28:27.420
Our final way of having a soft skill is to explain your work.

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:31.900
So the idea of a rubber duck is very popular in programming.

00:28:31.900 --> 00:28:35.420
You know, you have this little computer that's running a program.

00:28:35.500 --> 00:28:39.500
This little companion that you can sit there and talk to.

00:28:40.140 --> 00:28:43.660
And oftentimes when you're talking through your problems, your solutions just kind of

00:28:43.660 --> 00:28:44.619
fall out on their own.

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:49.500
So here's the thing that happens when you explain things.

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:55.020
Also from our Zen of Python, if the implementation is hard to explain, it's a bad idea.

00:28:55.819 --> 00:29:00.300
So, of course, being able to write documentation and things like that is helpful for the handoff

00:29:00.300 --> 00:29:02.939
of work when you're collaborating with others.

00:29:02.939 --> 00:29:08.540
But selfishly, oftentimes when you're explaining your work, you kind of are able to figure

00:29:08.540 --> 00:29:11.020
out what is a good idea and what isn't.

00:29:11.819 --> 00:29:16.459
Having clarity on the code that you're writing is really able to help you supercharge your

00:29:16.459 --> 00:29:22.060
own ability to comprehend the problems that you're solving and then build that build whatever

00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:23.020
you would like later.

00:29:24.540 --> 00:29:27.180
This is something that I saw, like, on Blue Sky.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:28.780
I don't know if you call this a tweet or not.

00:29:29.739 --> 00:29:32.780
But on Blue Sky, I think about this almost every single day.

00:29:33.579 --> 00:29:36.859
If your writing helps even one person, it's worth doing.

00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:39.819
Especially if that one person is you.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:43.900
And, of course, like the original context of this is literary people wanting to become

00:29:43.900 --> 00:29:44.459
an author.

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:50.219
But I think of this all the time when I'm looking for a new package to use.

00:29:50.219 --> 00:29:54.859
I want to see, you know, is there not only API documentation, you know, that reference

00:29:54.859 --> 00:29:57.660
page, but is there a getting started guide?

00:29:57.739 --> 00:29:59.900
Are there examples or some sort of a gallery?

00:30:01.180 --> 00:30:04.939
I also think about this when I'm writing functions for myself or for others.

00:30:06.219 --> 00:30:10.540
Things like doc strings and types, you know, it's not mandatory in Python.

00:30:10.540 --> 00:30:14.859
You can run wild, you know, make the craziest wild west of functions you desire.

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:20.699
But when you add types and doc strings to your functions, you can realize, you know,

00:30:20.699 --> 00:30:26.300
oh, this doesn't make too much sense, you know, this argument is just like the other

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:26.859
one.

00:30:26.859 --> 00:30:31.420
Or maybe you're like me and sometimes you add types and realize your scope is way too

00:30:31.420 --> 00:30:32.380
broad.

00:30:32.380 --> 00:30:34.219
And it also helps yourself.

00:30:34.219 --> 00:30:39.660
But, you know, it helps your users as well later to pick up this information and say,

00:30:39.660 --> 00:30:42.619
oh, I should be passing a pandas data frame here.

00:30:42.619 --> 00:30:43.900
I should be doing whatever.

00:30:45.180 --> 00:30:49.660
So, writing down your intent is super important, even if it's just for yourself.

00:30:52.140 --> 00:30:55.339
And the hard part can be, like, surfacing this information later.

00:30:56.140 --> 00:31:00.939
One more thing that I want to focus on is this help pane in Positron.

00:31:01.819 --> 00:31:05.020
So, if you just, like, write something in the console and, like, put a little question

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:10.219
mark next to it, it will pull up this pane and it gives your, like, it will render all

00:31:10.219 --> 00:31:15.260
of your doc strings and it has syntax, not really syntax highlighting, but, like, formatting,

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:22.219
like, rich API formatting for your NumPy and your Sphinx and your epi text formatted doc

00:31:22.219 --> 00:31:23.020
strings.

00:31:23.020 --> 00:31:27.260
If you're linking to other functions, all of your documentation is interlinked.

00:31:27.260 --> 00:31:32.060
So, it's helpful because you don't have to go all the way over to something like a doc

00:31:32.060 --> 00:31:34.939
site if you're just looking for something really quickly.

00:31:34.939 --> 00:31:39.180
You can also do this in Jupyter and IPython if you do, like, double question marks.

00:31:42.699 --> 00:31:47.500
So, it's really helping to, like, get this information closer to users, even if that

00:31:47.500 --> 00:31:56.140
user is just you, to really close this feedback loop between writing documentation and being

00:31:56.140 --> 00:31:57.739
able to use it again later.

00:31:58.859 --> 00:32:03.099
And docs, like, they're a good place to write things down, especially when it's specific

00:32:03.099 --> 00:32:04.219
to a certain function.

00:32:05.739 --> 00:32:11.180
But oftentimes I'll have, like, half-baked ideas or ideas that don't quite fit into the

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:12.540
types or a doc string.

00:32:13.339 --> 00:32:17.979
And sometimes these are my half-baked ideas on architecture or something like that.

00:32:18.619 --> 00:32:26.219
And this is where I have really enjoyed using something like a Claude MD file for things

00:32:26.219 --> 00:32:32.060
that, you know, it's not good enough or it's not fleshed out enough to go to a doc site.

00:32:32.060 --> 00:32:35.020
It's not going to be sent to my colleagues or anything like that.

00:32:35.660 --> 00:32:39.660
Because it turns out robots are really good at completing your half-baked ideas.

00:32:40.540 --> 00:32:45.900
You know, I think it's a great maintenance task for something that maybe you it's a project

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:50.540
you only do part of the time and you're going to put it down and pick it back up again in

00:32:50.540 --> 00:32:51.099
six months.

00:32:52.060 --> 00:32:57.500
It's a great place to write things like your architecture or the purpose of a certain function

00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.219
or if there's any gotchas for your project.

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:02.459
And maybe even, like, a happy path.

00:33:02.459 --> 00:33:07.500
Like, we should always want to use this data frame, pull from this database, something

00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:08.300
like that.

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:13.579
This is a great place to do, like, super lightweight, very low stakes documentation.

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:16.859
It's nice because it doesn't have to be as polished.

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:23.739
But if we think of, like, the open source virtue of release early and release often,

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:28.300
I want us to think about, like, share early and share often.

00:33:28.300 --> 00:33:32.619
You know, bring these thoughts out of your brain as early as possible so you can add

00:33:32.619 --> 00:33:34.140
clarity to your work later on.

00:33:35.099 --> 00:33:37.900
So, we want to think about tools really holistically.

00:33:37.900 --> 00:33:40.060
These hard skills, these soft skills.

00:33:40.859 --> 00:33:45.020
Like, we can think about, like, if we have this compass that it always points towards

00:33:45.020 --> 00:33:49.180
beautiful tools for ourselves and for others and always making sure that we're choosing

00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:54.060
the right tools for us to live our best lives as data practitioners.

00:33:54.619 --> 00:34:00.380
We want to consider, like, the input and the output of our work and take on as much complexity

00:34:00.939 --> 00:34:05.099
as we can as a builder to make a user's life easier.

00:34:07.099 --> 00:34:12.219
There's a lot of feedback loops, especially when you're building projects where people

00:34:12.219 --> 00:34:16.939
are using the tools you're building, noticing pain points, and sharing them with others.

00:34:16.939 --> 00:34:19.899
And this is how our ecosystem improves.

00:34:19.899 --> 00:34:23.020
You know, we're all both consumers and contributors.

00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:27.340
And everyone's unique perspective is really important as they bring in a different way

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:30.620
that they're traversing through this space.

00:34:31.899 --> 00:34:36.139
So, building tools, it's not about this, like, final destination of, like, the perfect

00:34:36.139 --> 00:34:38.219
package, the perfect report.

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:41.260
It's this journey that really never ends.

00:34:41.260 --> 00:34:45.500
You know, using tools reveals what's needed and what to build next.

00:34:46.300 --> 00:34:51.340
Building reveals what's possible, what we can build for others.

00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:54.300
And sharing really just cycles, starts this cycle anew.

00:34:54.379 --> 00:34:59.820
So, every great tool starts as someone's story of triumph or frustration.

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:04.540
So, all of your blog posts and your conference talks, your GitHub issues that you're opening,

00:35:04.540 --> 00:35:09.419
your LinkedIn posts that you're sharing, you know, sharing what works and what doesn't

00:35:09.419 --> 00:35:11.260
helps everyone improve.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:15.020
So, I would really encourage, you know, give feedback, because it matters.

00:35:15.659 --> 00:35:18.139
You know, your tools make other people's work better.

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:20.699
And your feedback makes our tools better.

00:35:21.419 --> 00:35:23.179
And your feedback makes our tools better.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:26.699
So, what makes tools stick?

00:35:26.699 --> 00:35:31.580
There's the hard skills of modularity, reproducibility, flexibility.

00:35:32.139 --> 00:35:37.899
There's also the soft skills of knowing your users and emphasizing discoverability, building

00:35:37.899 --> 00:35:41.979
things, building little things for big impact, and explaining your work.

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:47.580
This is all driven by a mission for people to have, like, the most beautiful experience

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:51.659
with the open source tools that they're using, and for people to feel empowered that they

00:35:51.659 --> 00:35:55.979
can build tools, you know, small, medium, or large.

00:35:57.340 --> 00:35:58.139
So, thank you all.

00:35:58.780 --> 00:35:59.899
There's a Posit booth.

00:35:59.899 --> 00:36:00.860
I'll be there.

