You can learn more about Positron at this site.

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:04.540
That's also my website.

00:36:04.540 --> 00:36:06.219
And I'll be taking questions now.

00:36:06.219 --> 00:36:06.620
Thank you.

00:36:06.620 --> 00:36:17.500
I don't know if people.

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:18.540
I'll start with the front.

00:36:19.179 --> 00:36:21.419
Yes, a question about the plotting pane.

00:36:22.139 --> 00:36:26.300
I see that you had a Matplotlib plot up there.

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:31.419
Do you support other plots or packages to Seaborn, Plotly, or anything like that?

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:37.659
The question was about Positron's plots pane and what sort of packages that we support.

00:36:38.379 --> 00:36:39.739
So, we support Matplotlib.

00:36:41.899 --> 00:36:47.179
Talking about modularity, most, actually, all Python plotting packages are built off

00:36:47.179 --> 00:36:48.219
of Matplotlib.

00:36:48.219 --> 00:36:51.659
So, we actually get a lot of support just from supporting Matplotlib.

00:36:52.540 --> 00:36:57.179
But other packages that we know work well are Plotly, Seaborn, Plot9.

00:36:57.580 --> 00:36:59.500
There's a whole bunch of others.

00:36:59.500 --> 00:37:03.100
But I think that's kind of the main ones that I can think of right now.

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:06.139
So, yes, many plots are supported.

00:37:06.139 --> 00:37:09.820
And if you ever find one that isn't and you would like it to be, open a GitHub issue and

00:37:09.820 --> 00:37:11.179
we can support that for you.

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:15.500
In the back.

00:37:16.620 --> 00:37:17.340
Thanks.

00:37:17.340 --> 00:37:22.300
You said that building for data scientists could be different than building for software

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:23.340
engineers.

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:27.179
There was a talk a couple years back called why software engineers and data scientists

00:37:27.179 --> 00:37:28.219
want to murder each other.

00:37:29.580 --> 00:37:35.179
But when you're going from a tool user to a tool builder, you are shifting your own mindset

00:37:35.179 --> 00:37:41.739
from a data scientist why to or what to an engineer's how.

00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:45.739
What's that shift like and how are you able to make that work?

00:37:46.379 --> 00:37:46.620
Yeah.

00:37:47.179 --> 00:37:54.219
Um, so the question is, when you go from data scientist to tool builder, these are, you

00:37:54.219 --> 00:38:00.300
know, I talked about they're two different skill sets and how to make them happy together

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:04.459
and how to, you know, live with the two wolves inside you, I suppose.

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:12.300
I think, like, a lot of what I think about is, like, the empathy for the data scientist

00:38:12.300 --> 00:38:14.939
leaks into you as a software engineer.

00:38:14.939 --> 00:38:20.780
They are a very different tool, like, different ideas, different skills in some ways.

00:38:21.899 --> 00:38:24.939
So I think knowing what the outcome is is important.

00:38:25.500 --> 00:38:29.899
For example, I'm trying to think.

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:36.939
Even, like, the plots pane, you know, my data science brain says we should be able to iterate

00:38:36.939 --> 00:38:38.620
through all of these lines.

00:38:39.580 --> 00:38:44.459
But the software engineer part of my brain says, okay, when we're using plots in a notebook,

00:38:44.540 --> 00:38:45.979
oftentimes it's all one chunk.

00:38:45.979 --> 00:38:47.820
So how do we make sure that both of these work?

00:38:48.379 --> 00:38:54.379
So I think it's, like, acknowledging that these are two different skills for software

00:38:54.379 --> 00:38:59.100
engineering, kind of, you know, a skill that I might be doing is I'm writing more end-to-end

00:38:59.100 --> 00:39:03.419
tests or unit tests or something like that that I might as a data scientist.

00:39:03.419 --> 00:39:07.179
But having that empathy of knowing the problems to solve is super important.

00:39:08.139 --> 00:39:09.419
So thank you for that question.

00:39:09.419 --> 00:39:14.939
I'll go here, and then I'll go over to you.

00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:15.820
Sure.

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:21.419
So my question is, one of the things you do is you build a lot of features for the IDE

00:39:21.419 --> 00:39:24.379
or in the process of, like, building small little tools into it, right?

00:39:24.379 --> 00:39:29.340
And what I wonder about is, like, what kind of signals or feedback do you use to figure

00:39:29.340 --> 00:39:32.459
out if this feature that you've just added was actually a good idea or not?

00:39:32.459 --> 00:39:35.580
Because, like, I mean, looking at my own experience, like, building a new feature,

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:37.820
you probably think it's a good idea, which is why you release it.

00:39:37.820 --> 00:39:40.860
But that doesn't mean that your users actually agree with your enthusiasm.

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:42.540
So how do you go about figuring that out?

00:39:42.540 --> 00:39:48.620
Yeah, the question is, you get a lot of feedback from people, and we build a lot of features.

00:39:48.620 --> 00:39:53.260
So how do we decide if, one, a feature is needed, and two, if not only is it needed,

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:55.899
but people actually want it, which are subtly different things?

00:39:58.379 --> 00:40:04.620
I think one thing, like, we're lucky enough we have an active online community of people

00:40:04.620 --> 00:40:09.260
who are willing to tell us, like, I want you to support X, Y, and Z.

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:12.860
So I think that is one way.

00:40:12.860 --> 00:40:17.179
And another is, like, the intuition of because we know our users.

00:40:18.459 --> 00:40:24.300
I think of, you know, I was really struggling with deploying Jupyter Notebooks,

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:29.580
or I was really struggling with transferring from this data science library to this one.

00:40:29.659 --> 00:40:33.659
So being able to infuse, like, our own knowledge of knowing the users

00:40:33.659 --> 00:40:35.340
is also a good place to start.

00:40:35.899 --> 00:40:39.020
I think asking questions is super reasonable.

00:40:39.020 --> 00:40:41.419
You know, saying, hey, I'm thinking about this.

00:40:42.139 --> 00:40:43.340
Is this something that would work?

00:40:43.979 --> 00:40:46.300
Is this something that makes sense from your stakeholders?

00:40:47.340 --> 00:40:51.899
Like, closing this feedback loop and not being afraid to just say, like, early on,

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:56.620
can we have feedback on this, even if it's as a prototype or something like that?

00:40:57.580 --> 00:41:01.659
So a lot of communication with users and trying to put yourself in their shoes

00:41:02.219 --> 00:41:04.139
for small, medium, and large features.

00:41:04.139 --> 00:41:05.500
All right.

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:06.060
Two more minutes.

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:07.419
So just, like, a question.

00:41:07.419 --> 00:41:07.899
Perfect.

00:41:08.699 --> 00:41:09.179
Yes.

00:41:09.179 --> 00:41:10.620
Isabel, I have a question.

00:41:10.620 --> 00:41:18.300
How do you encourage data science persona types to become tool builders?

00:41:21.260 --> 00:41:25.899
And the reason I'm asking this is because sometimes there's this psychological barrier

00:41:26.620 --> 00:41:27.820
to building tools.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.659
Like, they're like, I'm a tool consumer.

00:41:29.659 --> 00:41:30.860
I do not want to build.

00:41:31.419 --> 00:41:32.780
I just want to use the tools.

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:34.139
I just want to get my job done.

00:41:36.699 --> 00:41:38.699
Yeah, I'd like to hear some of your thoughts on that.

00:41:38.699 --> 00:41:43.580
Yeah, the question is, how do you convince people who identify as a tool consumer

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:44.620
to be a tool builder?

00:41:46.939 --> 00:41:48.939
There's a couple different ways that we can talk about this.

00:41:48.939 --> 00:41:54.939
I think one is the time is now because of the AI tools that are available.

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:59.340
I think the barrier to starting to build a Python package, like I said, is way lower.

00:41:59.340 --> 00:42:01.179
You can say, I have these functions.

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:05.739
Literally, copy and paste them into ChatGPT or Cloud or whatever.

00:42:05.739 --> 00:42:08.300
And be like, hey, can you make this into a Python package?

00:42:09.260 --> 00:42:12.860
I think data scientists love reproducibility.

00:42:12.860 --> 00:42:17.899
So if you can frame things in a reproducible way, this is really important because the

00:42:17.899 --> 00:42:22.860
more tools you build, it makes your work more reproducible by having these functions that

00:42:22.860 --> 00:42:23.580
you can reuse.

00:42:25.500 --> 00:42:27.580
So I think those are two important factors.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:34.860
Also, the more specialized something is for your task, I have this function for my specific

00:42:34.860 --> 00:42:38.139
data set, the faster they're going to be able to work.

00:42:38.139 --> 00:42:43.340
So even if it's just a small incremental tool of changing your script that you run all of

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:47.820
your data through into a function, congratulations, you've already become a tool builder.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:50.139
You're already taking steps onto this path.

00:42:50.780 --> 00:42:56.459
So I think the time is right to change our mindsets and just be a little bit of a tool

00:42:56.459 --> 00:42:58.860
builder as well as being a tool consumer.

00:43:03.100 --> 00:43:04.139
I'm getting cut off.

00:43:04.139 --> 00:43:06.379
I will be over, out, and around.

00:43:06.379 --> 00:43:07.739
Feel free to ask me any more questions.

00:43:07.739 --> 00:43:08.459
I'd love to chat.

